[{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = ThieleTiles","category":"page"},{"location":"#ThieleTiles","page":"Home","title":"ThieleTiles","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for ThieleTiles.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"This package is inspired by this paper by Steffen L. Lauritzen: http://web.math.ku.dk/~lauritzen/papers/ThieleOgGulvfliser.pdf (in Danish) abut the floow tiles designed by Thorvald Nicolai Thiele (1838-1910).","category":"page"},{"location":"#Background","page":"Home","title":"Background","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The tilings are based on rings of complex integers.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"In particular:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Gaussian integers: $ Z[i] = { x = a + ib \\in C | a, b \\in Z, i^2 = -1 } $\nEisenstein integers $ Z[\\omega] = { x = a + \\omega b \\in C | a, b \\in Z, \\omega = (1- i\\sqrt(3))/2) } $","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"There is a package implementing Gaussian integers using AbstratctAlgebra.jl https://github.com/ulthiel/GaussianIntegers.jl ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The examples described in the paper relate to Gaussian primes and Quadratic residues","category":"page"},{"location":"#Examples","page":"Home","title":"Examples","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Gaussian-Primes","page":"Home","title":"Gaussian Primes","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"A Gaussian integer z = a + ib is a gaussian prime iff one of the following holds:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"a*b != 0 and a^2 + b^2 is a prime (in Z)\na = 0 and |b| is prime and |b| == 3 mod 4\nb = 0 and |a| is prime and |a| == 3 mod 4","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Eg 7 is a Gaussian prime, but 5 is not.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"This packages implements a function to tile the lattice of complex integers according to this property.  As most gaussian integers are not primes, the function includes an option to invert the colors to get a mainly light tiling.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"using Plots\nusing ThieleTiles\n\nplot_gaussian_primes(100)\nplot_gaussian_primes(100; invert_colors = true)\n","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"(Image: Gaussian Primes)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"(Image: Gaussian Primes, invert_colors)","category":"page"},{"location":"#Quadratic-residues","page":"Home","title":"Quadratic residues","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Modules = [ThieleTiles]","category":"page"}]
